-- South African Stocks: Anglo, Esorfranki, FirstRand, Santam Move
-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n   a n d   R o b e r t   B r a n d
-- 2012-02-28T16:29:10Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-02-28/south-african-stocks-anglo-bhp-esorfranki-firstrand-implats.html
The  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index (JALSH) 
advanced the most in four weeks, rising 1 percent to 34,214.53
by the close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active equities in the
South African market today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  , the diversified miner that
makes up about 9 percent of the index, climbed 1.2 percent to
322.50 rand. Copper rose to a two-week high as German
legislators approved a second bailout for  Greece , and U.S. and
European gauges of economic confidence rose more than expected,
pointing to improving growth and metals demand.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BIL)  , the world’s biggest miner,
added 1.6 percent to 248.79 rand.  Curro Holdings Ltd. (COH)  (COH SJ), which owns and operates
private schools in  South Africa , fell to a four-month low after
saying it intends to raise 348 million rand ($46 million) in a
rights offer. The shares slumped 5.5 percent to 10.04 rand, the
lowest close since Nov. 24.  Esorfranki Ltd. (ESR)  , a provider of engineering
services to builders, gained for the first time in three days,
rising 1.5 percent to 1.34 rand. The company is still in talks
to buy a development business which has the rights to a mixed-
used, affordable housing development, it said in a statement
today.  FirstRand Ltd. (FSR)  , South Africa’s second-largest
banking group, advanced for the third day in four, gaining 1.2
percent to 24.25 rand. Earnings per share in 2010, adjusted to
exclude the effect of the disposal of the group’s insurance
assets, rose 26 percent to 1.02 rand, beating the 1-rand median
estimate of three analysts surveyed by Bloomberg.  Iliad Africa Ltd. (ILA)  , a distributor of tiles and
building materials, dropped 1.2 percent to 4.79 rand after
saying it will post a loss per share of as much as 180 cents for
the year through December.       Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd. (IMP)  , the second-largest
producer, added 0.6 percent to 163.90 rand, its third day of
advances in four. About 9,000 dismissed employees returned to
work at its Rustenburg mine in South Africa by yesterday, the
company said in an e-mailed reply to questions today.  Santam Ltd. (SNT)  , South Africa’s largest property and
casualty insurer, rose to its highest price on record after the
company announced a special dividend of 8.50 rand a share even
though full-year earnings per share before one-time items
declined to 12.16 rand compared with 13.67 rand a year earlier.
The shares climbed 5.9 percent to 163 rand.  To contact the reporters on this story:
